an: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dД“</i> вҖҳthighвҖҷ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Riley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names В© Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rИіge</i> вҖҳryeвҖҷ + <i>lД“ah</i> вҖҳwoodland clearingвҖҷ.","Irish: from <b>Г“ Raghailligh</b> вҖҳdescendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>вҖҷ, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Г“ Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Reily","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Riley  ."]},{"name":"Raleigh","meanings":["English: habitational name from Raleigh (House) in Pilton (Devon), recorded as <i>Radeleia</i> in 1086 and <i>Rawlegh</i> in 1535. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>rЗЈge</i> вҖҳroe deerвҖҷ + <i>lД“ah</i> вҖҳwoodland clearingвҖҷ.","Irish: variant of   Riley  .","History: The English explorer Sir Walter Raleigh (1554вҖ“1618) was born in Hayes Barton, Devon, into a family of Devon gentry. He was related to most of the West Country's important families, including that of Sir Francis Drake. His half-brother was the explorer Sir Humphrey Gilbert. In 1578 Raleigh was granted a patent to explore and colonize вҖңunknown landsвҖқ in America. In the 1580s he was granted extensive estates in Munster (Ireland), in reward for his suppression of the Desmond Rebellions."]},{"name":"Rawley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Riley  .","English and Irish: variant of   Raleigh  ."]},{"name":"Rilea","meanings":["Altered form of Irish   Riley  ."]},{"name":"Rahilly","meanings":["Irish (Kerry and Cork): perhaps from <b>Г“ Raghailligh</b> (see   Reilly  ), but more likely from the surname <b>Г“ Raithile</b> вҖҳdescendant of <i>Raithile</i>вҖҷ, a personal name of unexplained etymology. This surname is common in Munster, where it is also Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b>."]},{"name":"Rowley","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of various places called Rowley or Rowly, such as Rowley Regis (Staffordshire), Rowley (Devon, Durham), Rowleygreen Farm (Hertfordshire), Rowly (Surrey), Rowley (East Yorkshire), Rowley, near Bardsey (Yorkshire), Rowley in Lepton (Yorkshire), and Rowley Hill (Essex). The placenames probably all derive from Old English <i>rЕ«h</i> вҖҳroughвҖҷ + <i>lД“ah</i> вҖҳwoodland clearingвҖҷ, though the East Yorkshire place may have been named with <i>hlДҒw</i> вҖҳmound, hillвҖҷ as the second element.","Irish: from <b>Г“ Roghallaigh</b>, a variant of <b>Г“ Raghailligh</b>. See   Riley   and   O'Reilly  ."]},{"name":"Rylee","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of   Riley   or German <b>Reile</b>, <b>Reihle</b>, variants of   Reil  ."]},{"name":"Reel","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Г“ Raghaill</b> вҖҳdescendant of <i>Raghall</i>вҖҷ, a short form of the personal name <i>Raghailleach</i>; see   Riley   and compare   Riel  .","Americanized form of German   Riehl  .","Flemish: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Radilo</i>, itself a short form of a compound name formed with <i>rДҒd</i> вҖҳcounsel, adviceвҖҷ as the first element, for example <i>Radolf</i> (see   Ralph  )."]},{"name":"Relihan","meanings":["Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Г“ RoileachГЎin</b> вҖҳdescendant of RoileachГЎnвҖҷ. <i>RoileachГЎn</i> is a diminutive of the name <i>Roghallach</i> (see   Riley  )."]},{"name":"Rielly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Bridie.","English and Scottish: variant of   Riley  .","Irish: variant of   Reilly  ; see   O'Reilly  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names В© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> вҖҳwill, desireвҖҷ + <i>helm</i> вҖҳhelmet, protectionвҖҷ. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the вҖҳconqueredвҖҷ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":102,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the